# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: wifi-7
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] This standard aims to boost throughput in crowded places like offices and malls.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] Though the nominal data rate is only 37% higher than that of Wi-Fi 5, the throughput increases by at least four times, making it more efficient and reducing latency by 75%.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] The quintupling of overall throughput is made possible by higher spectral efficiency.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] Wi-Fi 6 has a main feature called OFDMA, similar to how cellular common-carrier networks work.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] This brings better spectrum use, improved power control to avoid interference, and enhancements like 1024‑QAM, MIMO and MU-MIMO for faster speeds.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] There are also reliability improvements such as lower power consumption and security protocols like Target Wake Time and WPA3.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] The 802.11ax standard was approved on September 1, 2020, with Draft 8 getting 95% approval.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] Subsequently, on February 1, 2021, the standard received official endorsement from the IEEE Standards Board.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] With the previous generation Wi-Fi 5, multi-user MIMO was introduced, which is a spatial multiplexing technique.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] MU-MIMO allows the access point to form beams towards each client, while transmitting information simultaneously.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] By doing so, the interference between clients is reduced, and the overall throughput is increased, since multiple clients can receive data simultaneously.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] With Wi-Fi 6, a similar multiplexing is introduced in the *frequency-division multiplexing*: OFDMA.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] With OFDMA, multiple clients are assigned to different Resource Units in the available spectrum.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] By doing so, an 80 MHz channel can be split into multiple Resource Units, so that multiple clients receive different types of data over the same spectrum, simultaneously.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] To support OFDMA, Wi-Fi 6 needs four times as many subcarriers as Wi-Fi 5.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] Since the available bandwidths have not changed and the number of subcarriers increases by a factor of four, the subcarrier spacing is reduced by the same factor.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] This introduces OFDM symbols that are four times longer: with Wi-Fi 5, an OFDM symbol takes 3.2 microseconds to transmit.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] With Wi-Fi 6, it takes 12.8 microseconds (both without guard intervals).
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] The 802.11ax amendment brings several key improvements over 802.11ac.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] While 802.11ac only uses the 5 GHz band, which is a bit over 700 MHz wide, 802.11ax also allows the use of the 2.4 GHz band of some earlier protocols, less than 100 MHz wide, and the larger 6 GHz band, about 1200 MHz wide.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] Wi-Fi 6E adds to Wi‑Fi 6 the use of the 6 GHz band and, thereby, channels that are 160 MHz wide without the restrictions of Dynamic Frequency Selection that apply to all 160 MHz channels in the 5 GHz band.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] The number and selection of channels available depends on the country a given Wi-Fi 6 network operates in.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] To meet the goal of supporting dense 802.11 deployments, the following features have been approved.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] Following the ratification of the IEEE 802.11ax standard in February 2021, Wi-Fi 6 saw rapid adoption across consumer and enterprise devices.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] The Wi-Fi Alliance began certifying Wi-Fi 6 devices under its *Wi-Fi CERTIFIED 6* program in September 2019, ahead of the standard's formal approval.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] Major smartphone, laptop, and router manufacturers incorporated Wi-Fi 6 support into their product lines beginning in 2020.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] IEEE 802.11y-2008 extended operation of 802.11a to the licensed 3.7 GHz band.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] Increased power limits allow a range up to 5,000 m.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] As of 2009, it is only being licensed in the United States by the FCC.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] Based on short guard interval; standard guard interval is ~10% slower.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] Rates vary widely based on distance, obstructions, and interference.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] For single-user cases only, based on default guard interval which is 0.8 microseconds.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] Since multi-user via OFDMA has become available for 802.11ax, these may decrease.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] Also, these theoretical values depend on the link distance, whether the link is line-of-sight or not, interferences and the multi-path components in the environment.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] The default guard interval is 0.8 microseconds.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11ax] However, 802.11ax extended the maximum available guard interval to 3.2 microseconds, in order to support outdoor communications, where the maximum possible propagation delay is larger compared to Indoor environments.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11be] In a single band, throughput reaches a theoretical maximum of 23 Gbit/s, although actual results are much lower.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11be] Development of the 802.11be amendment began with an initial draft in March 2021 and the final version was published on 22 July 2025.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11be] Despite this, numerous products were announced in 2022 based on draft standards, with retail availability in early 2023.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11be] On 8 January 2024, the Wi-Fi Alliance introduced its *Wi-Fi Certified 7* program to certify Wi-Fi 7 devices as the technical requirements were essentially complete.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11be] The 802.11be Task Group is led by individuals affiliated with Qualcomm, Intel, and Broadcom.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11be] Those affiliated with Huawei, Maxlinear, NXP, and Apple also have senior positions.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11be] The Wi-Fi Alliance maintains a list of Wi-Fi 7 certified devices.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11be] Android 13 and higher provide support for Wi-Fi 7.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11be] The Linux 6.2 kernel provides support for Wi-Fi 7 devices.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11be] The 6.4 kernel added Wi-Fi 7 mesh support.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11be] Linux 6.5 included significant driver support by Intel engineers, particularly support for MLO.
[src:wifi-7/ieee-802-11be] Support for Wi-Fi 7 was added to Windows 11, as of build 26063.1.
[src:wifi-7/multi-user-mimo] MU-MIMO extends single-user MIMO (SU-MIMO), where one multi-antenna transmitter communicates with one multi-antenna receiver.
[src:wifi-7/multi-user-mimo] It is closely related to space-division multiple access (SDMA), because users are separated by their spatial channel characteristics rather than only by time, frequency, or code resources.
[src:wifi-7/multi-user-mimo] MU-MIMO is used in cellular networks and wireless LAN systems, and is related to techniques such as massive MIMO, coordinated multipoint transmission and reception (CoMP), and cooperative MIMO.
[src:wifi-7/multi-user-mimo] In SU-MIMO, the antennas used for spatial multiplexing usually belong to one transmitter and one receiver.
[src:wifi-7/multi-user-mimo] In MU-MIMO, the spatial streams may be assigned to different users.
[src:wifi-7/multi-user-mimo] This can increase system throughput when the users have sufficiently distinct channel conditions.
[src:wifi-7/multi-user-mimo] The performance of MU-MIMO depends on the number of antennas, the accuracy of channel state information, scheduling, interference management, and the signal-processing techniques used at the transmitter and receiver.
[src:wifi-7/multi-user-mimo] The **MIMO broadcast channel** describes a downlink system in which one multi-antenna transmitter sends data to multiple receivers.
[src:wifi-7/multi-user-mimo] In wireless networks, this transmitter is commonly a base station or access point.
[src:wifi-7/multi-user-mimo] Downlink MU-MIMO usually requires the transmitter to have channel state information at the transmitter (CSIT).
[src:wifi-7/multi-user-mimo] This information is used for user scheduling, beamforming, and precoding.
[src:wifi-7/multi-user-mimo] If the transmitter has accurate CSIT, it can direct different spatial streams toward different users while reducing interference between them.
[src:wifi-7/multi-user-mimo] Precoding methods for the MIMO broadcast channel include dirty paper coding, zero-forcing precoding, block diagonalization, and other linear or hybrid precoding techniques.
[src:wifi-7/multi-user-mimo] The **MIMO multiple-access channel** describes an uplink system in which multiple users transmit to one multi-antenna receiver.
[src:wifi-7/multi-user-mimo] In cellular systems, the receiver is usually a base station; in wireless local-area networks, it may be an access point.
[src:wifi-7/multi-user-mimo] Uplink MU-MIMO relies on receiver-side processing to separate the users' signals.
[src:wifi-7/multi-user-mimo] Techniques include joint detection, interference cancellation, and SDMA-based scheduling.
[src:wifi-7/multi-user-mimo] Channel state information at the receiver (CSIR) is typically obtained from uplink pilot or reference signals.
[src:wifi-7/multi-user-mimo] Compared with downlink CSIT, receiver-side channel estimation is often simpler because the receiver can directly estimate the channels from the transmitted pilots.
[src:wifi-7/multi-user-mimo] MIMO MAC systems can outperform point-to-point MIMO systems when the receiver has enough antennas and processing capability to separate signals from multiple users.
[src:wifi-7/multi-user-mimo] Several wireless technologies are closely related to MU-MIMO.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi uses multiple parts of the IEEE 802 protocol family and is designed to work well with its wired sibling, Ethernet.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Compatible devices can network through wireless access points with each other as well as with wired devices and the Internet.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Different versions of Wi-Fi are specified by various IEEE 802.11 protocol standards, with different radio technologies determining radio bands, maximum ranges, and speeds that may be achieved.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi most commonly uses the 2.4 gigahertz (120 mm) UHF and 5 gigahertz (60 mm) SHF radio bands, with the 6 gigahertz SHF band used in newer generations of the standard; these bands are subdivided into multiple channels.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Channels can be shared between networks, but, within range, only one transmitter can transmit on a channel at a time.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi's radio bands work best for line-of-sight use.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Common obstructions, such as walls, pillars, home appliances, etc., may greatly reduce range, but this also helps minimize interference between different networks in crowded environments.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The range of an access point is about 20 m (66 ft) indoors, while some access points claim up to a 150 m (490 ft) range outdoors.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Hotspot coverage can be as small as a single room with walls that block radio waves or as large as many square kilometers using multiple overlapping access points with roaming permitted between them.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Over time, the speed and spectral efficiency of Wi-Fi has increased.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] As of 2025, some versions of Wi-Fi, running on suitable hardware at close range, can achieve speeds of 23 Gbit/s (gigabit per second).
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Federal Communications Commission released parts of the ISM bands for unlicensed use for communications in the United States.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] These frequency bands include the same 2.4 GHz bands used by equipment such as microwave ovens, and are thus subject to interference.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] In 1991 in the city of Nieuwegein in the Netherlands, the NCR Corporation and AT&T invented the precursor to 802.11, intended for use in cashier systems, under the name WaveLAN.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] NCR's Vic Hayes, who held the chair of IEEE 802.11 for ten years, along with Bell Labs engineer Bruce Tuch, approached the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) to create a standard and were involved in designing the initial 802.11b and 802.11a specifications within the IEEE.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] They have both been subsequently inducted into the Wi-Fi NOW Hall of Fame.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] In 1989 in Australia, a team of scientists began working on wireless LAN technology.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] A prototype test bed for a wireless local area network (WLAN) was developed in 1992 by a team of researchers from the Radiophysics Division of the CSIRO (Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation) in Australia, led by John O'Sullivan.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] A patent for Wi-Fi was lodged by the CSIRO in 1992.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The first version of the 802.11 protocol was released in 1997, and provided up to 2 Mbit/s link speeds.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] This was updated in 1999 with 802.11b to permit 11 Mbit/s link speeds.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] In 1999, the Wi-Fi Alliance formed as a trade association to hold the Wi-Fi trademark under which most IEEE 802.11 products are sold.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The major commercial breakthrough came with Apple Inc. adopting Wi-Fi for their iBook series of laptops in 1999.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] It was the first mass consumer product to offer Wi-Fi network connectivity, which was then branded by Apple as AirPort.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] This was in collaboration with the same group that helped create the standard: Vic Hayes, Bruce Tuch, Cees Links, Rich McGinn, and others from Lucent.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] In 2000, Radiata, a group of Australian scientists connected to the CSIRO, were the first to use the 802.11a standard on chips connected to a Wi-Fi network.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi uses a large number of patents held by multiple different organizations.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Australia, the United States and the Netherlands simultaneously claim the invention of Wi-Fi, and a consensus has not been reached globally.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] In 2009, the Australian CSIRO was awarded $200 million after a patent settlement with 14 technology companies, with a further $220 million awarded in 2012 after legal proceedings with 23 companies.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] In 2016, the CSIRO's WLAN prototype test bed was chosen as Australia's contribution to the exhibition *A History of the World in 100 Objects* held in the National Museum of Australia.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The name *Wi-Fi*, commercially used as early as August 1999, was coined by the brand-consulting firm Interbrand.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The Wi-Fi Alliance had hired Interbrand to create a name that was "a little catchier than 'IEEE 802.11b Direct Sequence'." According to Phil Belanger, a founding member of the Wi-Fi Alliance, the term *Wi-Fi* was chosen from a list of ten names that Interbrand proposed.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The yin-yang Wi-Fi logo indicates the certification of a product for interoperability.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The name is often written as *WiFi*, *Wifi*, or *wifi*, but these are not approved by the Wi-Fi Alliance.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] IEEE, a separate but related organization, has stated "WiFi is a short name for Wireless Fidelity" on their website.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The name *Wi-Fi* was partly chosen because it sounds similar to Hi-Fi, which consumers take to mean *high fidelity* or *high quality*.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Interbrand hoped consumers would find the name catchy, and that they would assume this *wireless* protocol has high fidelity because of its name.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Other technologies intended for fixed points, including Motorola Canopy, are usually called *fixed wireless*.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Alternative wireless technologies include Zigbee, Z-Wave, Bluetooth and mobile phone standards.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] To connect to a Wi-Fi LAN, a computer must be equipped with a wireless network interface controller.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The combination of a computer and an interface controller is called a *station*.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Stations are identified by one or more MAC addresses.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi nodes often operate in infrastructure mode in which all communications go through a base station.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] *Ad hoc mode* refers to devices communicating directly with each other, without communicating with an access point.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] A service set is the set of all the devices associated with a particular Wi-Fi network.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Devices in a service set need not be on the same wavebands or channels.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] A service set can be local, independent, extended, mesh, or a combination.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Each service set has an associated identifier, a 32-byte service set identifier (SSID), which identifies the network.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The SSID is configured within the devices that are part of the network.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] A basic service set (BSS) is a group of stations that share the same wireless channel, SSID, and other settings that have wirelessly connected, usually to the same access point.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Each BSS is identified by a MAC address called the *BSSID*.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The IEEE does not test equipment for compliance with their standards.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The Wi-Fi Alliance was formed in 1999 to establish and enforce standards for interoperability and backward compatibility, and to promote wireless local-area-network technology.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The Wi-Fi Alliance enforces the use of the Wi-Fi brand to technologies based on the IEEE 802.11 standards from the IEEE.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Manufacturers with membership in the Wi-Fi Alliance, whose products pass the certification process, gain the right to mark those products with the Wi-Fi logo.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Specifically, the certification process requires conformance to the IEEE 802.11 radio standards, the WPA and WPA2 security standards, and the EAP authentication standard.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Certification may optionally include tests of IEEE 802.11 draft standards, interaction with cellular-phone technology in converged devices, and features relating to security set-up, multimedia, and power-saving.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Not every Wi-Fi device is submitted for certification.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The lack of Wi-Fi certification does not necessarily imply that a device is incompatible with other Wi-Fi devices.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The Wi-Fi Alliance may or may not sanction derivative terms, such as Super Wi-Fi, coined by the US Federal Communications Commission (FCC) to describe proposed networking in the UHF TV band in the US.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Equipment frequently supports multiple versions of Wi-Fi.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] To communicate, devices must use a common Wi-Fi version.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The versions differ between the radio wavebands they operate on, the radio bandwidth they occupy, the maximum data rates they can support and other details.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Some versions permit the use of multiple antennas, which permits greater speeds as well as reduced interference.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Historically, the equipment listed the versions of Wi-Fi supported using the name of the IEEE standards.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] In 2018, the Wi-Fi Alliance introduced simplified Wi-Fi generational numbering to indicate equipment that supports Wi-Fi 4 (802.11n), Wi-Fi 5 (802.11ac) and Wi-Fi 6 (802.11ax).
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] These generations have a high degree of backward compatibility with previous versions.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The alliance has stated that the generational level 4, 5, or 6 can be indicated in the user interface when connected, along with the signal strength.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi technology may be used to provide local network and Internet access to devices that are within Wi-Fi range of one or more routers that are connected to the Internet.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The coverage of one or more interconnected access points can extend from an area as small as a few rooms to as large as many square kilometres.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Coverage in the larger area may require a group of access points with overlapping coverage.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] For example, public outdoor Wi-Fi technology has been used successfully in wireless mesh networks in London.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi provides services in private homes, businesses, as well as in public spaces.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi hotspots may be set up either free of charge or commercially, often using a captive portal webpage for access.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Organizations, enthusiasts, authorities and businesses, such as airports, hotels, and restaurants, often provide free or paid-use hotspots to attract customers, to provide services to promote business in selected areas.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Routers often incorporate a digital subscriber line modem or a cable modem and a Wi-Fi access point, are frequently set up in homes and other buildings, to provide Internet access for the structure.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Similarly, battery-powered routers may include a mobile broadband modem and a Wi-Fi access point.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] When subscribed to a cellular data carrier, they allow nearby Wi-Fi stations to access the Internet.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] A number of smartphones have a built-in mobile hotspot capability of this sort, though carriers often disable the feature, or charge a separate fee to enable it.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Standalone devices such as MiFi- and WiBro-branded devices provide the capability.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Some laptops that have a cellular modem card can also act as mobile Internet Wi-Fi access points.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Multiple traditional university campuses in the developed world provide at least partial Wi-Fi coverage.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Carnegie Mellon University built the first campus-wide wireless Internet network, called Wireless Andrew, at its Pittsburgh campus in 1993 before Wi-Fi branding existed.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] A number of universities collaborate in providing Wi-Fi access to students and staff through the Eduroam international authentication infrastructure.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] In the early 2000s, multiple cities around the world announced plans to construct citywide Wi-Fi networks.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] There are a number of successful examples; in 2004, Mysore (Mysuru) became India's first Wi-Fi-enabled city.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] A company called WiFiyNet has set up hotspots in Mysore, covering the whole city and a few nearby villages.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Cloud, Florida and Sunnyvale, California, became the first cities in the United States to offer citywide free Wi-Fi (from MetroFi).
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Minneapolis has generated $1.2 million in profit annually for its provider.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] In May 2010, the then London mayor Boris Johnson pledged to have London-wide Wi-Fi by 2012.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Several boroughs including Westminster and Islington already had extensive outdoor Wi-Fi coverage at that point.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] New York City announced a city-wide campaign to convert old phone booths into digital kiosks in 2014.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The project, titled LinkNYC, has created a network of kiosks that serve as public Wi-Fi hotspots, high-definition screens and landlines.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Installation of the screens began in late 2015.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The city government plans to implement more than seven thousand kiosks over time, eventually making LinkNYC the largest and fastest public, government-operated Wi-Fi network in the world.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The UK has planned a similar project across major cities of the country, with the project's first implementation in the London Borough of Camden.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Officials in South Korea's capital Seoul were moving to provide free Internet access at more than 10,000 locations around the city, including outdoor public spaces, major streets, and densely populated residential areas.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Seoul was planning to grant leases to KT, LG Telecom, and SK Telecom.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The companies were supposed to invest $44 million in the project, which was to be completed in 2015.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi positioning systems use known positions of Wi-Fi hotspots to identify a device's location.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] It is used when GPS isn't suitable due to issues like signal interference or slow satellite acquisition.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] This includes assisted GPS, urban hotspot databases, and indoor positioning systems.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi positioning relies on measuring signal strength (RSSI) and fingerprinting.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Parameters like SSID and MAC address are crucial for identifying access points.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The accuracy depends on nearby access points in the database.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Signal fluctuations can cause errors, which can be reduced with noise-filtering techniques.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] For low precision, integrating Wi-Fi data with geographical and time information has been proposed.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The Wi-Fi RTT capability introduced in IEEE 802.11mc allows for positioning based on round trip time measurement, an improvement over the RSSI method.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The IEEE 802.11az standard promises further improvements in geolocation accuracy.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi sensing is used in applications such as motion detection and gesture recognition.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi stations communicate by sending each other data packets, blocks of data individually sent and delivered over radio on various channels.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] As with all radio, this is done by the modulation and demodulation of carrier waves.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Different versions of Wi-Fi use different techniques, 802.11b uses direct-sequence spread spectrum on a single carrier, whereas 802.11a, Wi-Fi 4, 5 and 6 use orthogonal frequency-division multiplexing.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Channels are used half duplex and can be time-shared by multiple networks.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Any packet sent by one computer is locally received by stations tuned to that channel, even if that information is intended for just one destination.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Stations typically ignore information not addressed to them.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The use of the same channel also means that the data bandwidth is shared, so for example, available throughput to each device is halved when two stations are actively transmitting.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] As with other IEEE 802 LANs, stations come programmed with a globally unique 48-bit MAC address.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The MAC addresses are used to specify both the destination and the source of each data packet.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] On the reception of a transmission, the receiver uses the destination address to determine whether the transmission is relevant to the station or should be ignored.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] A scheme known as carrier-sense multiple access with collision avoidance (CSMA/CA) governs the way stations share channels.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] With CSMA/CA stations attempt to avoid collisions by beginning transmission only after the channel is sensed to be idle, but then transmit their packet data in its entirety.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] CSMA/CA cannot completely prevent collisions, as two stations may sense the channel to be idle at the same time and thus begin transmission simultaneously.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] A collision happens when a station receives signals from multiple stations on a channel at the same time.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] This corrupts the transmitted data and can require stations to re-transmit.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The lost data and re-transmission reduces throughput, in some cases severely.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The 802.11 standard provides several distinct radio frequency ranges for use in Wi-Fi communications: 900 MHz, 2.4 GHz, 3.6 GHz, 4.9 GHz, 5 GHz, 6 GHz and 60 GHz bands.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Each range is divided into a multitude of channels.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] In the standards, channels are numbered at 5 MHz spacing within a band (except in the 60 GHz band, where they are 2.16 GHz apart), and the number refers to the centre frequency of the channel.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Although channels are numbered at 5 MHz spacing, transmitters generally occupy at least 20 MHz, and standards allow for neighbouring channels to be bonded together to form a wider channel for higher throughput.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Countries apply their own regulations to the allowable channels, allowed users and maximum power levels within these frequency ranges.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] 802.11b/g/n can use the 2.4 GHz band, operating in the United States under FCC Part 15 rules and regulations.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] In this frequency band, equipment may occasionally suffer interference from microwave ovens, cordless telephones, USB 3.0 hubs, Bluetooth and other devices.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Spectrum assignments and operational limitations are not consistent worldwide: Australia and Europe allow for an additional two channels (12, 13) beyond the 11 permitted in the United States for the 2.4 GHz band, while Japan has three more (12–14).
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] 802.11a/h/j/n/ac/ax can use the 5 GHz U-NII band, which, for much of the world, offers at least 23 non-overlapping 20 MHz channels.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] This is in contrast to the 2.4 GHz frequency band where the channels are only 5 MHz wide.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] In general, lower frequencies have longer range but have less capacity.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The 5 GHz bands are absorbed to a greater degree by common building materials than the 2.4 GHz bands and usually give a shorter range.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] As 802.11 specifications evolved to support higher throughput, the protocols have become much more efficient in their bandwidth use.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Additionally, they have gained the ability to aggregate channels together to gain still more throughput where the bandwidth for additional channels is available.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] 802.11n allows for double radio spectrum bandwidth (40 MHz) per channel compared to 802.11a or 802.11g (20 MHz).
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] 802.11n can be set to limit itself to 20 MHz bandwidth to prevent interference in dense communities.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] In the 5 GHz band, 20 MHz, 40 MHz, 80 MHz, and 160 MHz channels are permitted with some restrictions, giving much faster connections.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi is part of the IEEE 802 protocol family.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The data is organized into 802.11 frames that are very similar to Ethernet frames at the data link layer, but with extra address fields.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] MAC addresses are used as network addresses for routing over the LAN.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi's MAC and physical layer (PHY) specifications are defined by IEEE 802.11 for modulating and receiving one or more carrier waves to transmit the data in the infrared, and 2.4, 3.6, 5, 6, or 60 GHz frequency bands.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] They are created and maintained by the IEEE LAN/MAN Standards Committee (IEEE 802).
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The base version of the standard was released in 1997 and has had many subsequent amendments.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The standard and amendments provide the basis for wireless network products using the Wi-Fi brand.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] While each amendment is officially revoked when incorporated in the latest version of the standard, the corporate world tends to market to the revisions because they concisely denote capabilities of their products.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] As a result, in the market place, each revision tends to become its own standard.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] In addition to 802.11, the IEEE 802 protocol family has specific provisions for Wi-Fi.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] These are required because Ethernet's cable-based media are not usually shared, whereas with wireless all transmissions are received by all stations within the range that employ that radio channel.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] While Ethernet has essentially negligible error rates, wireless communication media are subject to significant interference.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Therefore, the accurate transmission is not guaranteed so delivery is, therefore, a best-effort delivery mechanism.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Because of this, for Wi-Fi, the Logical Link Control (LLC) specified by IEEE 802.2 employs Wi-Fi's media access control (MAC) protocols to manage retries without relying on higher levels of the protocol stack.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] For internetworking purposes, Wi-Fi is usually layered as a link layer below the internet layer of the Internet Protocol.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] This means that nodes have an associated internet address and, with suitable connectivity, this allows full Internet access.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] In infrastructure mode, which is the most common mode used, all communications go through a base station.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi also allows communications directly from one computer to another without an access point intermediary.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] This is called *ad hoc* Wi-Fi transmission.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Different types of ad hoc networks exist.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] In the simplest case, network nodes must talk directly to each other.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] In more complex protocols nodes may forward packets, and nodes keep track of how to reach other nodes, even if they move around.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Ad hoc mode was first described by Chai Keong Toh in his 1996 patent of wireless ad hoc routing, implemented on Lucent WaveLAN 802.11a wireless on IBM ThinkPads over a size nodes scenario spanning a region of over a mile.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The success was recorded in *Mobile Computing* magazine (1999) and later published formally in *IEEE Transactions on Wireless Communications*, 2002 and *ACM SIGMETRICS Performance Evaluation Review*, 2001.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] This wireless ad hoc network mode has proven popular with multiplayer video games on handheld game consoles, such as the Nintendo DS and PlayStation Portable.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] It is also popular on digital cameras, and other consumer electronics devices.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Some devices can also share their Internet connection using ad hoc, becoming hotspots or virtual routers.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Similarly, the Wi-Fi Alliance promotes the specification Wi-Fi Direct for file transfers and media sharing through a new discovery and security methodology.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Another mode of direct communication over Wi-Fi is Tunneled Direct Link Setup (TDLS), which enables two devices on the same Wi-Fi network to communicate directly, instead of via the access point.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] An Extended Service Set may be formed by deploying multiple access points that are configured with the same SSID and security settings.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi client devices typically connect to the access point that can provide the strongest signal within that service set.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Increasing the number of Wi-Fi access points for a network provides redundancy, better range, support for fast handover, and increased overall network capacity by using more channels or by defining smaller cells.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Except for the smallest implementations (such as home or small office networks), Wi-Fi implementations have moved toward *thin* access points, with more of the network intelligence housed in a centralized network appliance, relegating individual access points to the role of dumb transceivers.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Outdoor applications may use mesh topologies.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi operational range depends on factors such as the frequency band, modulation technique, transmitter power output, receiver sensitivity, antenna gain and type, and propagation and interference characteristics in the environment.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] At longer distances, speed is typically reduced.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Compared to cell phones and similar technology, Wi-Fi transmitters are low-power devices.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] In general, the maximum amount of power that a Wi-Fi device can transmit is limited by local regulations, such as FCC Part 15 in the US.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Equivalent isotropically radiated power (EIRP) in the European Union is limited to 20 dBm (100 mW).
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi, however, has higher power compared to some other standards designed to support wireless personal area network applications.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] For example, Bluetooth provides a much shorter propagation range between 1 and 100 metres (1 and 100 yards) and so in general has a lower power consumption.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Other low-power technologies such as Zigbee have fairly long range, but much lower data rate.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The high power consumption of Wi-Fi makes battery life in some mobile devices a concern.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] On wireless routers with detachable antennas, it is possible to improve range by fitting upgraded antennas.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] An access point compliant with either 802.11b or 802.11g, using the stock omnidirectional antenna might have a range of 0.1 km.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The same radio with an external semi-parabolic antenna (15 dB gain) with a similarly equipped receiver at the far end might have a range of over 32 km.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Higher gain rating (dBi) indicates deviation from a theoretical, perfect isotropic radiator toward a directional antenna, and therefore the antenna can project or accept a usable signal further in particular directions, as compared to a similar output power on a more isotropic antenna.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] For example, an 8 dBi antenna used with a 100 mW driver has a similar horizontal range to a 6 dBi antenna being driven at 500 mW.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] This assumes that radiation in the vertical direction is not useful for communications.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi 4 and higher standards allow devices to have multiple antennas on transmitters and receivers.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Multiple antennas enable the equipment to exploit multipath propagation on the same frequency bands, giving higher speeds and more than doubled range.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The Wi-Fi 5 standard uses the 5 GHz band exclusively, and is capable of multi-station WLAN throughput of at least 1 gigabit per second, and a single station throughput of at least 500 Mbit/s.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] This standard uses several signal processing techniques such as multi-user MIMO and 4 × 4 spatial multiplexing streams, and wide channel bandwidth (160 MHz) to achieve its gigabit throughput.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] With Wi-Fi signals, line-of-sight usually works best, but signals can absorb, reflect, refract, diffract and fade through and around structures, both man-made and natural.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi signals are very strongly affected by metallic structures (including rebar in concrete, low-e coatings in glazing), rock structures (including marble) and water (such as found in vegetation).
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Due to the complex nature of radio propagation at typical Wi-Fi frequencies, particularly around trees and buildings, algorithms can only approximately predict Wi-Fi signal strength for any given area in relation to a transmitter.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Performance associated with long-range Wi-Fi is more easily predicted, since longer links typically operate line-of-sight from towers that transmit above the surrounding foliage.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Distance records (using non-standard devices) include 382 km (237 mi) in June 2007, held by Ermanno Pietrosemoli and EsLaRed of Venezuela, transferring about 3 MB/sec of data between the mountain-tops of El Águila and Platillon.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The Swedish National Space Agency transferred data 420 km (260 mi), using 6 watt amplifiers to reach an overhead stratospheric balloon.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi connections can be blocked or the network throughput lowered by having other devices in the same area.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi protocols are designed to share the radio bandwidth reasonably fairly.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Nevertheless, Wi-Fi networks are still susceptible to the hidden node and exposed node problems.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] A standard speed Wi-Fi signal occupies five channels in the 2.4 GHz band.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Adjacent-channel interference can be caused by overlapping channels.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Any two channel numbers that differ by five or more, such as 2 and 7, do not overlap.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Channels 1, 6, and 11 are the only *group of three* non-overlapping channels in North America.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] However, whether the overlap is significant depends on physical spacing.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Channels that differ by four interfere a negligible amount – much less than reusing channels (which causes co-channel interference) – if transmitters are at least a few metres apart.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] In Europe and Japan where channel 13 is available, using Channels 1, 5, 9, and 13 for 802.11g and 802.11n is viable and recommended.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] However, multiple 2.4 GHz 802.11b and 802.11g access points default to the same channel on initial startup, contributing to congestion on certain channels.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi pollution, or an excessive number of access points in the area, can prevent access and interfere with other devices' use of other access points, as well as decreasing overall signal-to-noise ratio (SNR).
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] These issues can become a problem in high-density areas, such as large apartment complexes or office buildings with multiple Wi-Fi access points.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] It is also an issue when municipalities or other large entities (such as universities) seek to provide large area coverage.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Other devices use the 2.4 GHz band: microwave ovens, ISM band devices, security cameras, Zigbee devices, Bluetooth devices, video senders, cordless phones, baby monitors, and, in some countries, amateur radio, all of which can cause significant additional interference.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] On some 5 GHz bands interference from radar systems can occur in some places.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Access points that support those bands employ dynamic frequency selection, which listens for radar, and if detected, will not permit transmission on that band.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] These bands can be used by low-power transmitters without a licence, and with few restrictions.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] However, while unintended interference is common, users who have been found to cause deliberate interference (particularly for attempting to locally monopolize these bands for commercial purposes) have been issued large fines.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Various layer-2 variants of IEEE 802.11 have different characteristics.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Across all flavours of 802.11, maximum achievable throughputs are either given based on measurements under ideal conditions or in the layer-2 data rates.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] This, however, does not apply to typical deployments in which data are transferred between two endpoints, of which at least one is typically connected to a wired infrastructure.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] This means that typically data frames pass an 802.11 (WLAN) medium and are converted to 802.3 (Ethernet) or vice versa.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Due to the difference in the frame (header) lengths of these two media, the packet size of an application determines the speed of the data transfer.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] This means that an application that uses small packets (e.g., VoIP) creates a data flow with higher overhead and lower information rate.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Other factors that contribute to the overall application data rate include the energy with which the wireless signal is received.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The latter is determined by distance and by the configured output power of the communicating devices.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi allows wireless deployment of local area networks (LANs).
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Also, spaces where cables cannot be run, such as outdoor areas and historical buildings, can host wireless LANs.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] However, building walls of certain materials, such as stone with high metal content, can block Wi-Fi signals.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] A Wi-Fi device is a short-range wireless device.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi devices are fabricated on RF CMOS integrated circuit (RF circuit) chips.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Since the early 2000s, manufacturers are building wireless network adapters into most laptops.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The price of chipsets for Wi-Fi continues to drop, making it an economical networking option included in ever more devices.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Different competitive brands of access points and client network-interfaces can inter-operate at a basic level of service.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Products designated as "Wi-Fi Certified" by the Wi-Fi Alliance are backward compatible.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Unlike mobile phones, any standard Wi-Fi device works anywhere in the world.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] A wireless access point (WAP) connects a group of wireless devices to an adjacent wired LAN.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] An access point resembles a network hub, relaying data between connected wireless devices in addition to a (usually) single connected wired device, most often an Ethernet hub or switch, allowing wireless devices to communicate with other wired devices.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wireless adapters allow devices to connect to a wireless network.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] These adapters connect to devices using various external or internal interconnects such as mini PCIe (mPCIe, M.2), USB, ExpressCard and previously PCI, Cardbus, and PC Card.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] As of 2010, most newer laptop computers come equipped with built-in internal adapters.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wireless routers integrate a Wireless Access Point, Ethernet switch, and internal router firmware application that provides IP routing, NAT, and DNS forwarding through an integrated WAN-interface.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] A wireless router allows wired and wireless Ethernet LAN devices to connect to a (usually) single WAN device such as a cable modem, DSL modem, or optical modem.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] A wireless router allows all three devices, mainly the access point and router, to be configured through one central utility.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] This utility is usually an integrated web server that is accessible to wired and wireless LAN clients and often optionally to WAN clients.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] This utility may also be an application that is run on a computer, as is the case with as Apple's AirPort, which is managed with the AirPort Utility on macOS and iOS.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wireless network bridges can act to connect two networks to form a single network at the data-link layer over Wi-Fi.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The main standard is the wireless distribution system (WDS).
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wireless bridging can connect a wired network to a wireless network.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] A bridge differs from an access point: an access point typically connects wireless devices to one wired network.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] A dual-band wireless bridge can also be used to enable 5 GHz wireless network operation on a device that only supports 2.4 GHz wireless and has a wired Ethernet port.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wireless range-extenders or wireless repeaters can extend the range of an existing wireless network.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Strategically placed range-extenders can elongate a signal area or allow for the signal area to reach around barriers such as those pertaining in L-shaped corridors.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wireless devices connected through repeaters suffer from an increased latency for each hop, and there may be a reduction in the maximum available data throughput.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Besides, the effect of additional users using a network employing wireless range-extenders is to consume the available bandwidth faster than would be the case whereby a single user migrates around a network employing extenders.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] For this reason, wireless range-extenders work best in networks supporting low traffic throughput requirements, such as for cases whereby a single user with a Wi-Fi-equipped tablet migrates around the combined extended and non-extended portions of the total connected network.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Also, a wireless device connected to any of the repeaters in the chain has data throughput limited by the "weakest link" in the chain between the connection origin and connection end.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Networks using wireless extenders are more prone to degradation from interference from neighbouring access points that border portions of the extended network and that happen to occupy the same channel as the extended network.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The security standard, Wi-Fi Protected Setup, allows embedded devices with a limited graphical user interface to connect to the Internet with ease.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi Protected Setup has 2 configurations: The Push Button configuration and the PIN configuration.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] These embedded devices are also called The Internet of things and are low-power, battery-operated embedded systems.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Several Wi-Fi manufacturers design chips and modules for embedded Wi-Fi, such as GainSpan.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Increasingly in the last few years (particularly as of 2007), embedded Wi-Fi modules have become available that incorporate a real-time operating system and provide a simple means of wirelessly enabling any device that can communicate via a serial port.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] This allows the design of simple monitoring devices.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] An example is a portable ECG device monitoring a patient at home.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] This Wi-Fi-enabled device can communicate via the Internet.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] These Wi-Fi modules are designed by OEMs so that implementers need only minimal Wi-Fi knowledge to provide Wi-Fi connectivity for their products.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] In June 2014, Texas Instruments introduced the first ARM Cortex-M4 microcontroller with an onboard dedicated Wi-Fi MCU, the SimpleLink CC3200.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] It makes embedded systems with Wi-Fi connectivity possible to build as single-chip devices, which reduces their cost and minimum size, making it more practical to build wireless-networked controllers into inexpensive ordinary objects.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The main issue with wireless network security is its simplified access to the network compared to traditional wired networks such as Ethernet.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] With wired networking, one must either gain access to a building (physically connecting into the internal network), or break through an external firewall.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] To access Wi-Fi, one must merely be within the range of the Wi-Fi network.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Most business networks protect sensitive data and systems by attempting to disallow external access.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Enabling wireless connectivity reduces security if the network uses inadequate or no encryption.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] An attacker who has gained access to a Wi-Fi network router can initiate a DNS spoofing attack against any other user of the network by forging a response before the queried DNS server has a chance to reply.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] A common measure to deter unauthorized users involves hiding the access point's name by disabling the SSID broadcast.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] While effective against the casual user, it is ineffective as a security method because the SSID is broadcast in the clear in response to a client SSID query.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Another method is to only allow computers with known MAC addresses to join the network, but determined eavesdroppers may be able to join the network by spoofing an authorized address.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wired Equivalent Privacy (WEP) encryption was designed to protect against casual snooping but it is no longer considered secure.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Tools such as AirSnort or Aircrack-ng can quickly recover WEP encryption keys.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Because of WEP's weakness the Wi-Fi Alliance approved Wi-Fi Protected Access (WPA) which uses TKIP.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] WPA was specifically designed to work with older equipment usually through a firmware upgrade.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Though more secure than WEP, WPA has known vulnerabilities.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The more secure WPA2 using Advanced Encryption Standard was introduced in 2004 and is supported by most new Wi-Fi devices.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] In 2017, a flaw in the WPA2 protocol was discovered, allowing a key replay attack, known as KRACK.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] A flaw in a feature added to Wi-Fi in 2007, called Wi-Fi Protected Setup (WPS), let WPA and WPA2 security be bypassed.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The only remedy as of 2011 was to turn off Wi-Fi Protected Setup, which is not always possible.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Virtual private networks can be used to improve the confidentiality of data carried through Wi-Fi networks, especially public Wi-Fi networks.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] A URI using the Wi-Fi scheme can specify the SSID, encryption type, password/passphrase, and if the SSID is hidden or not, so users can follow links from QR codes, for instance, to join networks without having to manually enter the data.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] A MeCard-like format is supported by Android and iOS 11+.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi access points typically default to an encryption-free (*open*) mode.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Novice users benefit from a zero-configuration device that works out-of-the-box, but this default does not enable any wireless security, providing open wireless access to a LAN.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] To turn security on requires the user to configure the device, usually via a software graphical user interface (GUI).
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] On unencrypted Wi-Fi networks connecting devices can monitor and record data (including personal information).
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Such networks can only be secured by using other means of protection, such as a VPN, or Hypertext Transfer Protocol over Transport Layer Security (HTTPS).
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The older wireless-encryption standard, Wired Equivalent Privacy (WEP), has been shown easily breakable even when correctly configured.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi Protected Access (WPA) encryption, which became available in devices in 2003, aimed to solve this problem.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Wi-Fi Protected Access 2 (WPA2) ratified in 2004 is considered secure, provided a strong passphrase is used.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] The 2003 version of WPA has not been considered secure since it was superseded by WPA2 in 2004.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] In 2018, WPA3 was announced as a replacement for WPA2, increasing security; it rolled out on 26 June.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Piggybacking refers to access to a wireless Internet connection by bringing one's computer within the range of another's wireless connection, and using that service without the subscriber's explicit permission or knowledge.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] During the early popular adoption of 802.11, providing open access points for anyone within range to use was encouraged to cultivate wireless community networks, particularly since people on average use only a fraction of their downstream bandwidth at any given time.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Recreational logging and mapping of other people's access points have become known as wardriving.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Indeed, many access points are intentionally installed without security turned on so that they can be used as a free service.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Providing access to one's Internet connection in this fashion may breach the Terms of Service or contract with the Internet service provider (ISP).
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] These activities do not result in sanctions in most jurisdictions; however, legislation and case law differ considerably across the world.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] A proposal to leave graffiti describing available services was called warchalking.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Piggybacking often occurs unintentionally – a technically unfamiliar user might not change the default "unsecured" settings to their access point and operating systems can be configured to connect automatically to any available wireless network.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] A user who happens to start up a laptop in the vicinity of an access point may find the computer has joined the network without any visible indication.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] Moreover, a user intending to join one network may instead end up on another one if the latter has a stronger signal.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] In combination with automatic discovery of other network resources (see DHCP and Zeroconf) this could lead wireless users to send sensitive data to the wrong middle-man when seeking a destination (see man-in-the-middle attack).
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p01] For example, a user could inadvertently use an unsecured network to log into a website, thereby making the login credentials available to anyone listening, if the website uses an insecure protocol such as plain HTTP without TLS.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p02] Wireless Internet access has become much more embedded in society.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p02] It has thus changed how the society functions in a number of ways.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p02] As of 2017 over half the world did not have access to the Internet, prominently rural areas in developing nations.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p02] Technology that has been implemented in more developed nations is often costly and energy inefficient.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p02] This has led to developing nations using more low-tech networks, frequently implementing renewable power sources that can solely be maintained through solar power, creating a network that is resistant to disruptions such as power outages.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p02] For instance, in 2007, a 450-kilometre (280 mi) network between Cabo Pantoja and Iquitos in Peru was erected in which all equipment is powered only by solar panels.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p02] These long-range Wi-Fi networks have two main uses: offer Internet access to populations in isolated villages, and to provide healthcare to isolated communities.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p02] In the case of the latter example, it connects the central hospital in Iquitos to 15 medical outposts which are intended for remote diagnosis.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p02] Access to Wi-Fi in public spaces such as cafés or parks allows people, in particular freelancers, to work remotely.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p02] While the accessibility of Wi-Fi is the strongest factor when choosing a place to work (75% of people would choose a place that provides Wi-Fi over one that does not), other factors influence the choice of specific hotspots.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p02] These vary from the accessibility of other resources, like books, the location of the workplace, and the social aspect of meeting other people in the same place.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p02] Moreover, the increase of people working from public places results in more customers for local businesses thus providing an economic stimulus to the area.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p02] Additionally, in the same study it has been noted that wireless connection provides more freedom of movement while working.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p02] Both when working at home or from the office it allows the displacement between different rooms or areas.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p02] In some offices (notably Cisco offices in New York) the employees do not have assigned desks but can work from any office connecting their laptop to Wi-Fi hotspot.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p02] The Internet has become an integral part of living.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p02] As of 2016, 81.9% of American households have Internet access.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p02] Additionally, 89% of American households with broadband connect via wireless technologies.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p02] 72.9% of American households have Wi-Fi.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p02] Wi-Fi networks have also affected how the interior of homes and hotels are arranged.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p02] For instance, architects have described that their clients no longer wanted only one room as their home office, but would like to work near the fireplace or have the possibility to work in different rooms.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p02] This contradicts architect's pre-existing ideas of the use of rooms that they designed.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p02] Additionally, some hotels have noted that guests prefer to stay in certain rooms since they receive a stronger Wi-Fi signal.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p02] The World Health Organization (WHO) says, "no health effects are expected from exposure to RF fields from base stations and wireless networks", but notes that they promote research into effects from other RF sources.
[src:wifi-7/wi-fi-p02] The United Kingdom's Health Protection Agency reported in 2007 that exposure to Wi-Fi for a year results in the "same amount of radiation from a 20-minute mobile phone call".
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] A **wireless LAN** (**WLAN**) is a wireless computer network that links two or more devices using wireless communication to form a local area network (LAN) within a limited area such as a home, school, computer laboratory, campus, or office building.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] This gives users the ability to move around within the area and remain connected to the network.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] Through a gateway, a WLAN can also provide a connection to the wider Internet.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] Wireless LANs based on the IEEE 802.11 standards are the most widely used computer networks in the world.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] These are commonly called Wi-Fi, which is a trademark belonging to the Wi-Fi Alliance.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] They are used for home and small office networks that link together laptop computers, printers, smartphones, Web TVs and gaming devices through a wireless network router, which in turn may link them to the Internet.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] Hotspots provided by routers at restaurants, coffee shops, hotels, libraries, and airports allow consumers to access the internet with portable wireless devices.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] Norman Abramson, a professor at the University of Hawaiʻi, developed the world's first wireless computer communication network, ALOHAnet.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] The system became operational in 1971 and included seven computers deployed over four islands to communicate with the central computer on the Oahu island without using phone lines.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] Wireless LAN hardware initially cost so much that it was only used as an alternative to cabled LAN in places where cabling was difficult or impossible.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] Early development included industry-specific solutions and proprietary protocols, but at the end of the 1990s these were replaced by technical standards, primarily the various versions of IEEE 802.11 (in products using the Wi-Fi brand name).
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] In 1990 CSIRO researchers began working on strategies for increasing the efficacy of wireless networks, specifically targeting methods of reducing the delay of receiving information.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] The team, which built upon John O´Sullivan`s findings on the Fourier Transform in the 1970s, has been credited as an integral part of the development of the modern infrastructure used globally.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] Beginning in 1991, a European alternative known as HiperLAN/1 was pursued by the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI) with a first version approved in 1996.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] This was followed by a HiperLAN/2 functional specification with ATM influences accomplished February 2000.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] Neither European standard achieved the commercial success of 802.11, although much of the work on HiperLAN/2 has survived in the physical specification (PHY) for IEEE 802.11a, which is nearly identical to the PHY of HiperLAN/2.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] It operates in both the 2.4 GHz and 5 GHz bands at a maximum data transfer rate of 600 Mbit/s.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] Most newer routers are *dual-band* and able to utilize both wireless bands.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] This allows data communications to avoid the crowded 2.4 GHz band, which is also shared with Bluetooth devices and microwave ovens.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] The 5 GHz band also has more channels than the 2.4 GHz band, permitting a greater number of devices to share the space.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] Not all WLAN channels are available in all regions.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] A HomeRF group formed in 1997 to promote a technology aimed at residential use, but it disbanded in January 2003.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] All components that can connect into a wireless medium in a network are referred to as stations.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] All stations are equipped with wireless network interface controllers.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] Wireless stations fall into two categories: wireless access points (WAPs) and clients.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] WAPs are base stations for the wireless network.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] They transmit and receive radio frequencies for wireless-enabled devices to communicate with.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] Wireless clients can be mobile devices such as laptops, personal digital assistants, VoIP phones and other smartphones, or non-portable devices such as desktop computers, printers, and workstations that are equipped with a wireless network interface.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] The basic service set (BSS) is a set of all stations that can communicate with each other at PHY layer.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] Every BSS has an identification (ID) called the BSSID, which is the MAC address of the access point servicing the BSS.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] There are two types of BSS: Independent BSS (also referred to as IBSS), and infrastructure BSS.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] An independent BSS (IBSS) is an ad hoc network that contains no access points, which means they cannot connect to any other basic service set.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] In an IBSS the STAs are configured in ad hoc (peer-to-peer) mode.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] An extended service set (ESS) is a set of connected BSSs.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] Access points in an ESS are connected by a distribution system.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] Each ESS has an ID called the SSID which is a 32-byte (maximum) character string.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] A distribution system (DS) connects access points in an extended service set.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] The concept of a DS can be used to increase network coverage through roaming between cells.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] Current wireless distribution systems are mostly based on WDS or Mesh protocols, though other systems are in use.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] The IEEE 802.11 has two basic modes of operation: *infrastructure* and *ad hoc* mode.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] In ad hoc mode, mobile units communicate directly peer-to-peer.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] In infrastructure mode, mobile units communicate through a wireless access point (WAP) that also serves as a bridge to other networks such as a local area network or the Internet.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] Many access points will also offer Wi-Fi Protected Setup, a quick, but no longer considered secure, method of joining a new device to an encrypted network.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] Most Wi-Fi networks are deployed in *infrastructure mode*.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] In infrastructure mode, wireless clients, such as laptops and smartphones, connect to the WAP to join the network.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] The WAP usually has a wired network connection and may have permanent wireless connections to other WAPs.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] WAPs are usually fixed and provide service to their client nodes within range.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] Some networks will have multiple WAPs using the same SSID and security arrangement.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] In that case, connecting to any WAP on that network joins the client to the network, and the client software will try to choose the WAP that gives the best service, such as the WAP with the strongest signal.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] An ad hoc network is a network where stations communicate only peer-to-peer (P2P).
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] There is no base and no one gives permission to talk.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] This is accomplished using the Independent Basic Service Set (IBSS).
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] A Wi-Fi Direct network is a different type of wireless network where stations communicate peer-to-peer.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] In a peer-to-peer network wireless devices within range of each other can discover and communicate directly without involving central access points.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] In a Wi-Fi P2P group, the group owner operates as an access point and all other devices are clients.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] There are two main methods to establish a group owner in the Wi-Fi Direct group.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] In one approach, the user sets up a P2P group owner manually.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] This method is also known as *autonomous group owner* (*autonomous GO*).
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] In the second method, called *negotiation-based group creation*, two devices compete based on the group owner intent value.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] The device with higher intent value becomes a group owner and the second device becomes a client.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] IEEE 802.11 defines the PHY and medium access control (MAC) layers based on carrier-sense multiple access with collision avoidance (CSMA/CA).
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] This is in contrast to Ethernet which uses carrier-sense multiple access with collision detection (CSMA/CD).
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] The 802.11 specification includes provisions designed to minimize collisions because mobile units have to contend with the hidden node problem where two mobile units may both be in range of a common access point, but out of range of each other.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] A bridge can be used to connect networks, typically of different types.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] A wireless Ethernet bridge allows the connection of devices on a wired Ethernet network to a wireless network.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] The bridge acts as the connection point to the wireless LAN.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] A wireless distribution system (WDS) enables the wireless interconnection of access points in an IEEE 802.11 network.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] It allows a wireless network to be expanded using multiple access points without the need for a wired backbone to link them, as is traditionally required.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] The notable advantage of a WDS over some other solutions is that it preserves the MAC addresses of client packets across links between access points.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] An access point can be either a main, relay, or remote base station.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] A main base station is typically connected to the wired Ethernet.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] A relay base station relays data between remote base stations, wireless clients or other relay stations to either a main or another relay base station.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] A remote base station accepts connections from wireless clients and passes them to relay or main stations.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] Because data is forwarded wirelessly, consuming wireless bandwidth, throughput in this method is halved for wireless clients not connected to a main base station.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] Connections between base stations are done at layer-2 and do not involve or require layer-3 IP addresses.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] WDS capability may also be referred to as repeater mode because it appears to bridge and accept wireless clients at the same time (unlike traditional bridging).
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] All base stations in a WDS must be configured to use the same radio channel and share WEP keys or WPA keys if they are used.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] They can be configured to different service set identifiers.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] WDS also requires that every base station be configured to forward to others in the system as mentioned above.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] **External roaming:** The MS (client) moves into a WLAN of another wireless Internet service provider (WISP) and takes their services.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] The user can use a foreign network independently from their home network, provided that the foreign network allows visiting users on their network.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] There must be special authentication and billing systems for mobile services in a foreign network.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] WLAN signals often extends beyond the boundaries of a building and can create coverage where it is unwanted, offering a channel through which non-residents or other unauthorized people could compromise a system and retrieve personal data.
[src:wifi-7/wireless-lan] To prevent this, it is usually sufficient to enforce the use of authentication, encryption, or a VPN that requires a password for network connectivity.
